<p><a name="End"></a><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="4"><b>End executions</b></font><br>
<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="2"><b>By Leah Siegel</b></font><p>

<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">BURLINGTON, Vt.--On June 16, a federal court sentenced Donald Fell to death by lethal injection. <p>
Fell was sentenced to death, despite the fact that Vermont abolished the death penalty in 1987, and no one has been executed in the state since 1954. Because the case crossed state borders, however, it fell under federal jurisdiction. The case became a way for the federal government to re-introduce the death penalty in a state where it has been abolished. <p>
After the sentencing, Vermonters Against the Death Penalty held a press conference where speakers from the New England area voiced their opposition to the death penalty. Local anti-death penalty activist Rachel Lawler said that she opposes the death penalty because it is "racist, executes the poor and is geographically biased." <p>
For those reasons, it's time to put an end to the death penalty once and for all. <p>

